/span></h2><p class="c11"><span class="c2"></span></p><a id="t.c6672c21d0633c3a4b50a501fcf0224f11a0df0a"></a><a id="t.1"></a><table class="c13"><tr class="c7"><td class="c37" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><h2 class="c25 c53" id="h.yklgp4a6uoq3"><span class="c48"></span></h2><p class="c41 c25"><span class="c2">1 ________________________________________________________History</span></p><p class="c29 c25"><span class="c2">1.1 Significant historical Events </span></p><p class="c41 c25"><span class="c2">2________________________________________________________Strategies</span></p><p class="c29 c25"><span class="c2">2.1 Systematic Trading</span></p><p class="c29 c25"><span class="c2">2.2 Trading ahead of index fund rebalancing</span></p><p class="c29 c25"><span class="c2">2.3 Pairs trading</span></p><p class="c29 c25"><span class="c2">2.4 Delta-neutral strategies</span></p><p class="c29 c25"><span class="c2">2.5 Arbitrage</span></p><p class="c29 c25"><span class="c2">2.5.1 Conditions for arbitrage</span></p><p class="c29 c25"><span class="c2">2.6 Mean reversion</span></p><p class="c29 c25"><span class="c2">2.7 Scalping</span></p><p class="c29 c25"><span class="c2">2.8 Transaction cost reduction</span></p><p class="c29 c25 c82"><span class="c2"></span></p><p class="c41 c25"><span class="c2">3______________________________________________________High-frequency trading</span></p><p class="c29 c25"><span class="c2">3.1 Market making</span></p><p class="c29 c25"><span class="c2">3.2 Statistical arbitrage</span></p><p class="c29 c25"><span class="c2">3.3 Event arbitrage</span></p><p class="c29 c25"><span class="c2">3.4 Spoofing</span></p><p class="c25 c29"><span class="c2">3.5 Quote stuffing</span></p><p class="c41 c25"><span class="c2">4_________________________________________________Low latency trading systems</span></p><p class="c41 c25"><span class="c2">5_____________________________________________________Strategy implementation</span></p><p class="c11 c25"><span class="c2"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c2"></span></p><p class="c11"><span class="c2"></span></p></td></tr></table><p class="c11"><span class="c2"></span></p></td></tr></table><p class="c19 c25"><span class="c2">&nbsp;</span></p><p class="c19 c25"><span>&nbsp;</span><hr style="page-break-before:always;display:none;"></p><p class="c0"><span class="c2"></span></p><p class="c6 title" id="h.7jrmjsff1zhy"><span class="c18"></span></p><a id="t.b618ec8b0b8ac56f8e18ae25496121bfca1935e7"></a><a id="t.2"></a><table class="c13"><tr class="c7"><td class="c51" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><h1 class="c61 c86" id="h.94ixs4wzldmf"><span class="c35">Introduction</span></h1><a id="t.259d544becfd745937280f8ed20f7c9ca705ae6c"></a><a id="t.3"></a><table class="c13"><tr class="c7"><td class="c37" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c19 c25"><span class="c2">Algorithmic trading is a type of automated trading that relies on pre-programmed rules to execute orders as quickly as possible. It attempts to increase the speed of computer transactions relative to human traders, who may be slower and more prone to error. Some investors use algorithmic trading because it allows them to place large orders without the time and expense associated with manually executing those trades themselves. Studies have shown that around 92% of trading in the Forex market is performed by algorithms rather than humans; many banks and other financial institutions also use algorithms in their operations.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c2"></span></p><p class="c19 c25"><span class="c2">The term &quot;algorithmic trading&quot; is often used to describe automated trading systems, which encompass a variety of trading strategies and rely on specialised software. These strategies include systematic trading, market making, intermarket spreading, arbitrage, or pure speculation such as trend following.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c2"></span></p><p class="c19 c25"><span class="c2">&nbsp;</span></p><p class="c6 title" id="h.z1sykvse1b1m"><span class="c2"></span></p><p class="c11"><span class="c18"></span></p></td></tr></table><p class="c11"><span class="c18"></span></p></td></tr></table><p class="c6 title" id="h.b8jh6yyepu93"><span class="c18"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c2"></span></p><hr style="page-break-before:always;display:none;"><p class="c0"><span class="c2"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c2"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c2"></span></p><a id="t.697f6d164061ef97be1e5a93f6d67e7b4e348004"></a><a id="t.4"></a><table class="c13"><tr class="c7"><td class="c51" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><h1 class="c25 c28" id="h.laqqcyhjt5tv"><span class="c35">Significant historical Events</span></h1><p class="c11"><span class="c2"></span></p><a id="t.dbaf2ea1fc4c43bbf4384fbc0f46f51de5a42603"></a><a id="t.5"></a><table class="c13"><tr class="c7"><td class="c37" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c19 c25"><span class="c2">In the 1990s, electronic communication networks (ECNs) were introduced to the financial markets. These networks allow investors to trade stocks and currencies outside of traditional exchanges. Beginning in 2001, the minimum tick size on U.S. stock exchanges was reduced from US$0.0625 per share to US$0.01 per share, which may have encouraged algorithmic trading as it changed market microstructure by permitting smaller differences between bid and offer prices, decreasing market-makers&#39; trading advantage.</span></p><p class="c19 c25"><span class="c2">This increased market liquidity led to institutional traders splitting up orders according to computer algorithms so they could execute orders at a better average price. In doing so, they abandoned the use of volume-weighted averages in favour of time-weighted averages, which measure the average price over a specific period of time.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c2"></span></p><p class="c19 c25"><span class="c2">A further encouragement for the adoption of algorithmic trading in the financial markets came in 2001 when a team of IBM researchers published a paper at the International Joint Conference on Artificial Intelligence where they showed that in experimental laboratory versions of the electronic auctions used in the financial markets, two algorithmic strategies (IBM&#39;s own MGD, and Hewlett-Packard&#39;s ZIP) could consistently out-perform human traders. MGD was a modified version of the &quot;GD&quot; algorithm invented by Steven Gjerstad &amp; John Dickhaut in 1996 the ZIP algorithm had been invented at HP by Dave Cliff (professor) in 1996.</span></p><p class="c19 c25"><span class="c2">In their 2005 paper, the IBM team wrote that their results showed MGD and ZIP outperforming human traders &quot;...might be measured in billions of dollars annually&quot;; this generated international media coverage.</span></p><p class="c19 c25"><span class="c2">As more electronic markets opened, other algorithmic trading strategies were introduced. Computers could react rapidly to price changes and observe several markets simultaneously. Many broker-dealers offered these strategies to their clients - differentiating them by behaviour, options and branding. Examples include Chameleon (developed by BNP Paribas), Stealth (developed by Deutsche Bank), Sniper and Guerilla (developed by Credit Suisse). These implementations adopted practices from the investing approaches of arbitrage, statistical arbitrage, trend following and mean reversion.</span></p><p class="c25 c95"><span class="c2">Case studies Profitability projections by the TABB Group, a financial services industry research firm, for the US equities HFT industry were US$1.3 billion before expenses for 2014, significantly down on the maximum of US$21 billion that the 300 securities firms and hedge funds that then specialised in this type of trading took in profits in 2008, which the authors had then called &quot;relatively small&quot; and &quot;surprisingly modest&quot; when compared to the market&#39;s overall trading volume.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c2"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c2"></span></p><p class="c19 c25"><span class="c2">Algorithmic trading and HFT have been the subject of much public debate since the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission and the Commodity Futures Trading Commission said in reports that an algorithmic trade entered by a mutual fund company triggered a wave of selling that led to the 2010 Flash Crash.The same reports found HFT strategies may have contributed to subsequent volatility by rapidly pulling liquidity from the market. As a result of these events, the Dow Jones Industrial Average suffered its second largest intraday point swing ever to that date, though prices quickly recovered. (See List of largest daily changes in the Dow Jones Industrial Average.) A July 2011 report by the International Organisation of Securities Commissions (IOSCO), an international body of securities regulators, concluded that while &quot;algorithms and HFT technology have been used by market participants to manage their trading and risk, their usage was also clearly a contributing factor in the flash crash event of May 6, 2010.&quot;However, other researchers have reached a different conclusion. One 2010 study found that HFT did not significantly alter trading inventory during the Flash Crash. Some algorithmic trading ahead of index fund rebalancing transfers profits from investors.</span></p></td></tr></table><p class="c11"><span class="c2"></span></p></td></tr></table><p class="c0"><span class="c2"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c2"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c2"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c2"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c2"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c2"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c2"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c2"></span></p><h3 class="c25 c15 c76" id="h.5aizf42sxay3"><span class="c32"></span></h3><h1 class="c25 c15 c63" id="h.6iew2qmz0f0d"><span class="c35"></span></h1><h1 class=